<br>
Actually, that's the second part of the experiment. For Gip's test, we're just checking the chance of success, so as long as there is sufficient mana left after the first cast to cast a low-mana spell (in the 5 to 10 range), then we can count that as a successful spec skill check.  Thus, any variability in the amount of the reduction (even ignoring the fact that I saw a consistent mana reduction % on successess) shouldn't affect my estimate of a 5% failure rate at max spec.<br>
<br>
The second part of the test does try to determine the size of the mana reduction (and whether it is variable or constant).  I'll have to dig out my notes on my prior post on this, but the mana reduction from my tests was a consistant amount about 13% to 15%.  Thus, after casting a 300 point spell, I appeared to have 43 to 45 mana left with a successful check.  Consistently.<br>
<br>
Yes, Verant could have changed things since then.  I invite folks to go out and do some testing of their own and report it back here.  <br>
<br>
BTW, I didn't key off ticks.  When I got close to the amount needed to cast the spell (yes, you can visually estimate this point with experience), I would start spam-casting (call it 0.5 seconds between attempts if you want).   That way, I would start casting as soon as I had sufficient mana.  Time consuming?  Yes.<br>
<br>
